## Pagination and Filtering

Using pagination The results can be filtered by date or number.  Traversal is possible using the number filters.

## Traversal/Pagination

Pagination is achieved through the use of the `before_number` or `after_number` filters.  By default, the records are returned in descending `number` order, i.e. newest receipts first.  With each response, a `next` link is provided when there are more results.

### Example

Consider a Site with 1000 Sales, numbered 1 through 1000.

#### First Request in Traversal

```
GET /sales
{
  "links": {
    "self": "https://acme.chargify.com/sales",
    "next": "https://acme.chargify.com/sales?before_number=981"
  },
  "meta": {
    "total": 1000,
    "count": 20
  },
  "data": [
    { number: 1000, ...},
    ... 18 more records ....
    { number: 981, ...}
  ]
}
```

#### Next Request in Traversal

```
GET /sales?before_number=981
{
  "links": {
    "self": "https://acme.chargify.com/sales?before_number=981",
    "next": "https://acme.chargify.com/sales?before_number=961"
  },
  "meta": {
    "total": 980,
    "count": 20
  },
  "data": [
    { number: 980, ...},
    ... 18 more records ....
    { number: 961, ...}
  ]
}
```

#### Last Request in Traversal

```
GET /sales?before_number=21
{
  "links": {
    "self": "https://acme.chargify.com/sales?before_number=21",
    "next": null
  },
  "meta": {
    "total": 20,
    "count": 20
  },
  "data": [
    { number: 20, ...},
    ... 18 more records ....
    { number: 1, ...}
  ]
}
```

#### Subsequent Fetches

Now that we have ingested "all" of the Sales for the Site, and we have recorded that our highest `number` was 1000, we can periodically poll to get the new Sales, always using our new highest number processed:

```
GET /sales?after_number=1000
{
  "links": {
    "self": "https://acme.chargify.com/sales?after_number=1000",
    "next": null
  },
  "meta": {
    "total": 3,
    "count": 3
  },
  "data": [
    { number: 1003, ...},
    { number: 1002, ...},
    { number: 1001, ...}
  ]
}
```

